webpackJsonp([0xffdac5e236b2],{406:function(e,t){e.exports={data:{site:{siteMetadata:{title:"Mike Herchel",author:"Mike Herchel"}},markdownRemark:{id:"/Users/mherchel/sites/herchel-new/src/blog/2018-01-28-from-sublime-to-vscode/index.md absPath of file >>> MarkdownRemark",html:'<p>On every new project I try to change one or two tools and/or techniques. </p>\n<p>This is a good balance, because if I change too many things, I get bogged down in the details and complexity of new tools ‚Äî but if I change nothing, I never get the chance to learn these new tools, and increase my productivity.</p>\n<p>For my current project, I‚Äôm switching my text-editor from Sublime Text to <a href="https://code.visualstudio.com/">Visual Studio Code</a>.</p>\n<p>\n  <a\n    class="gatsby-resp-image-link"\n    href="/static/computer-picture-e6cfddbb6f63edbc18f1f8fdada6a6c2-5a312.jpg"\n    style="display: block"\n    target="_blank"\n    rel="noopener"\n  >\n  \n  <span\n    class="gatsby-resp-image-wrapper"\n    style="position: relative; display: block; ; max-width: 800px; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;"\n  >\n    <span\n      class="gatsby-resp-image-background-image"\n      style="padding-bottom: 65.8%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url(\'data:image/jpeg;base64,\'); background-size: cover; display: block;"\n    >\n      <img\n        class="gatsby-resp-image-image"\n        style="width: 100%; height: 100%; margin: 0; vertical-align: middle; position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; box-shadow: inset 0px 0px 0px 400px white;"\n        alt="Photo of my computer with VSCode open"\n        title=""\n        src="/static/computer-picture-e6cfddbb6f63edbc18f1f8fdada6a6c2-893a4.jpg"\n        srcset="/static/computer-picture-e6cfddbb6f63edbc18f1f8fdada6a6c2-bbf57.jpg 200w,\n/static/computer-picture-e6cfddbb6f63edbc18f1f8fdada6a6c2-260b8.jpg 400w,\n/static/computer-picture-e6cfddbb6f63edbc18f1f8fdada6a6c2-893a4.jpg 800w,\n/static/computer-picture-e6cfddbb6f63edbc18f1f8fdada6a6c2-5a312.jpg 1000w"\n        sizes="(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px"\n      />\n    </span>\n  </span>\n  \n  </a>\n    </p>\n<h2>Why the switch?</h2>\n<p>I‚Äôve been using <a href="https://www.sublimetext.com/">Sublime</a> for over 5 years (wow ‚Äî time goes fast). I‚Äôve been hearing from some coworkers and friends that Visual Studio Code has really great JavaScript syntax highlighting and is just <em>nice</em>.</p>\n<blockquote class="twitter-tweet" data-lang="en"><p lang="en" dir="ltr">What text editor are you using for programming these days?</p>&mdash; Smashing Magazine (@smashingmag) <a href="https://twitter.com/smashingmag/status/951924123357376512?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw">January 12, 2018</a></blockquote>\n<p>I saw the tweet above as I was writing this article, which further solidifies the experiment.</p>\n<h2>My background and perspective</h2>\n<p>I‚Äôve been developing for the web since 2001, and I started out using Macromedia Dreamweaver and stuck with that through the end of the decade (using the code-only view for the majority of this time).</p>\n<figure>\n    \n  <a class="gatsby-resp-image-link" href="/static/dw-d156a0d9958c17cf5b8659714a2a57f1-5a312.jpg" style="display: block" target="_blank" rel="noopener">\n  \n  <span class="gatsby-resp-image-wrapper" style="position: relative; display: block; ; max-width: 800px; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;">\n    <span class="gatsby-resp-image-background-image" style="padding-bottom: 64.6%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url(&apos;data:image/jpeg;base64,&apos;); background-size: cover; display: block;">\n      <img class="gatsby-resp-image-image" style="width: 100%; height: 100%; margin: 0; vertical-align: middle; position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; box-shadow: inset 0px 0px 0px 400px white;" alt="Dreamweaver Screenshot" title="" src="/static/dw-d156a0d9958c17cf5b8659714a2a57f1-893a4.jpg" srcset="/static/dw-d156a0d9958c17cf5b8659714a2a57f1-bbf57.jpg 200w,\n/static/dw-d156a0d9958c17cf5b8659714a2a57f1-260b8.jpg 400w,\n/static/dw-d156a0d9958c17cf5b8659714a2a57f1-893a4.jpg 800w,\n/static/dw-d156a0d9958c17cf5b8659714a2a57f1-5a312.jpg 1000w" sizes="(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px">\n    </span>\n  </span>\n  \n  </a>\n    \n    <figcaption>Yes I do still have Dreamweaver installed &#x2014; I use it to edit email markup :)</figcaption>\n</figure>\n<p>In 2012, I switched to Sublime Text 2, which was amazing. It was fast, lightweight, and clean. I installed various plugins including Emmet, ESLint, Sass, and more. I especially liked the multiple cursors functionality. </p>\n<figure>\n    \n  <a class="gatsby-resp-image-link" href="/static/sublime-ad58e22ab9dc99a0e2bb5ac35b0018de-5a312.jpg" style="display: block" target="_blank" rel="noopener">\n  \n  <span class="gatsby-resp-image-wrapper" style="position: relative; display: block; ; max-width: 800px; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;">\n    <span class="gatsby-resp-image-background-image" style="padding-bottom: 70.1%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url(&apos;data:image/jpeg;base64,&apos;); background-size: cover; display: block;">\n      <img class="gatsby-resp-image-image" style="width: 100%; height: 100%; margin: 0; vertical-align: middle; position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; box-shadow: inset 0px 0px 0px 400px white;" alt="Sublime Text Screenshot" title="" src="/static/sublime-ad58e22ab9dc99a0e2bb5ac35b0018de-893a4.jpg" srcset="/static/sublime-ad58e22ab9dc99a0e2bb5ac35b0018de-bbf57.jpg 200w,\n/static/sublime-ad58e22ab9dc99a0e2bb5ac35b0018de-260b8.jpg 400w,\n/static/sublime-ad58e22ab9dc99a0e2bb5ac35b0018de-893a4.jpg 800w,\n/static/sublime-ad58e22ab9dc99a0e2bb5ac35b0018de-5a312.jpg 1000w" sizes="(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px">\n    </span>\n  </span>\n  \n  </a>\n    \n    <figcaption>Screenshot of Sublime Text.</figcaption>\n</figure>\n<p>I also started using PHPStorm, not just for PHP, but for jQuery. I liked the built in intellisense (autocomplete, quick info, list parameters, etc) that was offered in PHPStorm, but not in Sublime.</p>\n<figure>\n    \n  <a class="gatsby-resp-image-link" href="/static/phpstorm-f01b075059d910b72ba21271649cb5ca-5a312.jpg" style="display: block" target="_blank" rel="noopener">\n  \n  <span class="gatsby-resp-image-wrapper" style="position: relative; display: block; ; max-width: 800px; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;">\n    <span class="gatsby-resp-image-background-image" style="padding-bottom: 69%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url(&apos;data:image/jpeg;base64,&apos;); background-size: cover; display: block;">\n      <img class="gatsby-resp-image-image" style="width: 100%; height: 100%; margin: 0; vertical-align: middle; position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; box-shadow: inset 0px 0px 0px 400px white;" alt="PHPStorm Screenshot" title="" src="/static/phpstorm-f01b075059d910b72ba21271649cb5ca-893a4.jpg" srcset="/static/phpstorm-f01b075059d910b72ba21271649cb5ca-bbf57.jpg 200w,\n/static/phpstorm-f01b075059d910b72ba21271649cb5ca-260b8.jpg 400w,\n/static/phpstorm-f01b075059d910b72ba21271649cb5ca-893a4.jpg 800w,\n/static/phpstorm-f01b075059d910b72ba21271649cb5ca-5a312.jpg 1000w" sizes="(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px">\n    </span>\n  </span>\n  \n  </a>\n    \n    <figcaption>Screenshot of PHPStorm showing some fancy jQuery that I authored.</figcaption>\n</figure>\n<h3>What I didn‚Äôt like about Sublime</h3>\n<p>Sublime is fast, but it‚Äôs bare-bones. In order to get to a nice configuration, you need to install and configure many plugins such as <a href="https://packagecontrol.io/packages/Package%20Control">Package Control</a>, <a href="https://packagecontrol.io/packages/Emmet">Emmet</a>, <a href="https://packagecontrol.io/packages/SideBarEnhancements">Sidebar Enhancements</a>, <a href="https://packagecontrol.io/packages/SublimeLinter">Sublime Linter</a>, <a href="https://packagecontrol.io/packages/BracketHighlighter">Bracket Highlighter</a>, etc.</p>\n<p>Sublime requires a lot of configuration, it has questionable syntax highlighting, and linting integration not super tight (even with Sublime Linter).</p>\n<h3>What I didn‚Äôt like about PHPStorm</h3>\n<p>PHPStorm seemed slow and a bit confusing. It‚Äôs slow to open ‚Äî and although it‚Äôs very feature packed, it‚Äôs frequently hard to find what you‚Äôre looking to do. To be fair, the more I‚Äôve been using it, the more I know my way around the UI.</p>\n<h2>About Visual Studio Code</h2>\n<p>VSCode is <em>weird</em>. It‚Äôs created by Microsoft, which gives it away for free. In addition to Windows, they also support OSX and Linux. Weird. </p>\n<p>It‚Äôs built on top of <a href="https://electronjs.org/">Electron</a>, which allows for the development of desktop apps using Chromium and Node.</p>\n<p>VSCode occupies the sweet spot between IDE and text editor. It‚Äôs fairly quick to launch ‚Äî although not as quick as Sublime Text. But, that‚Äôs not a huge deal. It‚Äôs quick enough, and I don‚Äôt frequently relaunch it. While the editor is open, the runtime seems just as fast üòé.</p>\n<p>\n  <a\n    class="gatsby-resp-image-link"\n    href="/static/vscode-c7299a5e89825df3bf77ec632f1e5fe4-5a312.jpg"\n    style="display: block"\n    target="_blank"\n    rel="noopener"\n  >\n  \n  <span\n    class="gatsby-resp-image-wrapper"\n    style="position: relative; display: block; ; max-width: 800px; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;"\n  >\n    <span\n      class="gatsby-resp-image-background-image"\n      style="padding-bottom: 62.8%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url(\'data:image/jpeg;base64,\'); background-size: cover; display: block;"\n    >\n      <img\n        class="gatsby-resp-image-image"\n        style="width: 100%; height: 100%; margin: 0; vertical-align: middle; position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; box-shadow: inset 0px 0px 0px 400px white;"\n        alt="Visual Studio Code Screenshot"\n        title=""\n        src="/static/vscode-c7299a5e89825df3bf77ec632f1e5fe4-893a4.jpg"\n        srcset="/static/vscode-c7299a5e89825df3bf77ec632f1e5fe4-bbf57.jpg 200w,\n/static/vscode-c7299a5e89825df3bf77ec632f1e5fe4-260b8.jpg 400w,\n/static/vscode-c7299a5e89825df3bf77ec632f1e5fe4-893a4.jpg 800w,\n/static/vscode-c7299a5e89825df3bf77ec632f1e5fe4-5a312.jpg 1000w"\n        sizes="(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px"\n      />\n    </span>\n  </span>\n  \n  </a>\n    </p>\n<p>VSCode comes with a number of features enabled out of the box. Let‚Äôs take a look. </p>\n<h2>Feature: Better usability than other editors</h2>\n<p>VSCode takes into account the <em>little things</em> that happen when editing. </p>\n<p>One of my favorite examples is that when you start dragging to collapse the sidebar, it will completely disappear when it gets under a minimum width ‚Äî because this is what you‚Äôre intending to do! </p>\n<p>When you want to expand the sidebar back, you can either drag it, <em>or</em> you can click on the <em>files</em> icon within the left menu bar. This makes it dead-easy for newcomers to figure out the operation.</p>\n<p>VSCode also has much of the functionality of Sublime‚Äôs popular plugins already integrated. This makes it quicker to get up and running, and requires no configuration. VSCode includes functionality similar to <a href="https://packagecontrol.io/packages/Package%20Control">Package Control</a>, <a href="https://packagecontrol.io/packages/Emmet">Emmet</a>, <a href="https://packagecontrol.io/packages/SideBarEnhancements">Sidebar Enhancements</a>, <a href="https://packagecontrol.io/packages/BracketHighlighter">Bracket Highlighter</a>, and more. This makes <em>a lot</em> of sense, because the vast majority of users are going to make use of these at a given point.</p>\n<p>More little usability wins worth mentioning:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>When deleting from my directory tree, VSCode will send the file to my trash as opposed to just deleting it.</li>\n<li>You can drag and drop files to move them around your directory tree.</li>\n<li>Easy to use git tools (more on this later).</li>\n<li>Easy to use find and replace functionality.</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Feature: Intellisense / Autocomplete just ‚Äúworks‚Äù</h2>\n<p>Intellisense includes autocomplete, quick info, list parameters, and more. And, it‚Äôs enabled out of the box in VSCode. If you‚Äôre using JavaScript, it seems to work great ‚Äî on par with PHPStorm and better than Sublime. I have yet to use VSCode with PHP.</p>\n<figure border>\n    <video width="100%" autoplay controls loop muted>\n      <source src="/intellisense-6c15e76258c37f8a842daed4e0e010d0.mp4" type="video/mp4">\n    </video>\n    <figcaption>Automatic completion in VSCode</figcaption>\n</figure>\n<h2>Feature: VSCode‚Äôs plugin management is top notch</h2>\n<p>VSCode‚Äôs plugin handling is great. It‚Äôs easier than Sublime‚Äôs plugin handling, which is all text based.</p>\n<ol>\n<li>The plugin management interface is easy to find. The plugin dashboard has its own icon to the left of the directory tree.</li>\n<li>It will recommend plugins to you based on the types of files that you open. If I open lots of markdown files, it will recommend a popular markdown plugin. If I open lots of JavaScript files, it will show me plugins for that.</li>\n<li>It allows you to install plugins through the GUI. Normally, I like to use keyboard shortcuts for everything. But, installing plugins is not a normal day-to-day activity. Browsing, choosing, installing, and configuring plugins is easier through a graphical interface.</li>\n<li>It shows your currently installed plugins, and allows you to disable/uninstall them easily. This makes it easy to test-drive and compare plugins.</li>\n<li>You can easily search for new plugins using the GUI, or just show the most popular plugins for you to explore.</li>\n</ol>\n<figure>\n    \n  <a class="gatsby-resp-image-link" href="/static/plugin-interface-annotated-d0a4ecb64c434d81f17bacec335ba2e2-62b88.png" style="display: block" target="_blank" rel="noopener">\n  \n  <span class="gatsby-resp-image-wrapper" style="position: relative; display: block; ; max-width: 800px; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;">\n    <span class="gatsby-resp-image-background-image" style="padding-bottom: 64.38467807660962%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url(&apos;data:image/png;base64,&apos;); background-size: cover; display: block;">\n      <img class="gatsby-resp-image-image" style="width: 100%; height: 100%; margin: 0; vertical-align: middle; position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; box-shadow: inset 0px 0px 0px 400px white;" alt="Annotated screeshot of VSCode&apos;s plugin interface" title="" src="/static/plugin-interface-annotated-d0a4ecb64c434d81f17bacec335ba2e2-42603.png" srcset="/static/plugin-interface-annotated-d0a4ecb64c434d81f17bacec335ba2e2-f931c.png 200w,\n/static/plugin-interface-annotated-d0a4ecb64c434d81f17bacec335ba2e2-e8031.png 400w,\n/static/plugin-interface-annotated-d0a4ecb64c434d81f17bacec335ba2e2-42603.png 800w,\n/static/plugin-interface-annotated-d0a4ecb64c434d81f17bacec335ba2e2-5b8b9.png 1200w,\n/static/plugin-interface-annotated-d0a4ecb64c434d81f17bacec335ba2e2-62b88.png 1227w" sizes="(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px">\n    </span>\n  </span>\n  \n  </a>\n    \n    <figcaption>Annotated screeshot of VSCode&apos;s plugin interface.</figcaption>\n</figure>\n<h3>Tip: Plugins that I currently have installed**</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><a href="https://github.com/HookyQR/VSCodeBeautify">Beautify</a> reformats and reindents your JavaScript, CSS, HTML and more.</li>\n<li><a href="https://github.com/mastazi/VS-code-drupal">Drupal Syntax Highlighting</a> does exactly what you think it does :)</li>\n<li><a href="https://github.com/Microsoft/vscode-eslint">ESLint</a> provides integration with the popular ESLint JavaScript linting engine. This highlights syntax errors and code formatting issues in your JavaScript.</li>\n<li><a href="https://github.com/neilsustc/vscode-markdown">Markdown All in One</a> provides additional functionality for markdown including <code>CMD</code> + <code>B</code> to bold your text, and <code>CMD</code> + <code>I</code> to italicize.</li>\n<li><a href="https://github.com/bartosz-antosik/vscode-spellright">Spell Right</a> is a spellchecker for VSCode.</li>\n<li><a href="https://github.com/Microsoft/vscode-sublime-keybindings">Sublime Text Keymap</a> adds additional keymaps similar to Sublime Text for VSCode. </li>\n<li><a href="https://github.com/vscode-icons/vscode-icons">VSCode Icons</a> gives you a different icon for each type of file within your file explorer. This makes it much easier to find the file you‚Äôre looking for.</li>\n<li><a href="https://github.com/styled-components/vscode-styled-components">VSCode-styled-components</a> allows for CSS highlighting, indentation, and autocomplete when you‚Äôre using CSS in JS solutions like <a href="https://github.com/emotion-js/emotion">Emotion</a>.</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Feature: Git Integration</h2>\n<p>In the past, I‚Äôve been a command-line git user. This includes managing branches, commits, merges, and even conflicts.</p>\n<p>That being said, VSCode‚Äôs git integration is <em>nice</em>. </p>\n<figure>\n    \n  <a class="gatsby-resp-image-link" href="/static/gitdiff-840787c94fef37c9b5828b9440e15d02-6fdd2.png" style="display: block" target="_blank" rel="noopener">\n  \n  <span class="gatsby-resp-image-wrapper" style="position: relative; display: block; ; max-width: 800px; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;">\n    <span class="gatsby-resp-image-background-image" style="padding-bottom: 58.599999999999994%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url(&apos;data:image/png;base64,&apos;); background-size: cover; display: block;">\n      <img class="gatsby-resp-image-image" style="width: 100%; height: 100%; margin: 0; vertical-align: middle; position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; box-shadow: inset 0px 0px 0px 400px white;" alt="Screenshot of VSCode showing a git diff" title="" src="/static/gitdiff-840787c94fef37c9b5828b9440e15d02-42603.png" srcset="/static/gitdiff-840787c94fef37c9b5828b9440e15d02-f931c.png 200w,\n/static/gitdiff-840787c94fef37c9b5828b9440e15d02-e8031.png 400w,\n/static/gitdiff-840787c94fef37c9b5828b9440e15d02-42603.png 800w,\n/static/gitdiff-840787c94fef37c9b5828b9440e15d02-6fdd2.png 1000w" sizes="(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px">\n    </span>\n  </span>\n  \n  </a>\n    \n    <figcaption>VSCode diff feature makes changes easy to understand.</figcaption>\n</figure>\n<p>Out of the box, VSCode also highlights changes within the code view. </p>\n<figure>\n    \n  <a class="gatsby-resp-image-link" href="/static/notcommitted-461d30f0b2d7cc9e5356e7408a93ad05-bb3f1.png" style="display: block" target="_blank" rel="noopener">\n  \n  <span class="gatsby-resp-image-wrapper" style="position: relative; display: block; ; max-width: 800px; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;">\n    <span class="gatsby-resp-image-background-image" style="padding-bottom: 41.86851211072665%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url(&apos;data:image/png;base64,&apos;); background-size: cover; display: block;">\n      <img class="gatsby-resp-image-image" style="width: 100%; height: 100%; margin: 0; vertical-align: middle; position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; box-shadow: inset 0px 0px 0px 400px white;" alt="Screenshot of VSCode highlighting changes in code view" title="" src="/static/notcommitted-461d30f0b2d7cc9e5356e7408a93ad05-42603.png" srcset="/static/notcommitted-461d30f0b2d7cc9e5356e7408a93ad05-f931c.png 200w,\n/static/notcommitted-461d30f0b2d7cc9e5356e7408a93ad05-e8031.png 400w,\n/static/notcommitted-461d30f0b2d7cc9e5356e7408a93ad05-42603.png 800w,\n/static/notcommitted-461d30f0b2d7cc9e5356e7408a93ad05-bb3f1.png 1156w" sizes="(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px">\n    </span>\n  </span>\n  \n  </a>\n    \n    <figcaption>VSCode diff feature makes changes easy to understand.</figcaption>\n</figure>\n<p>VSCode has a really slick git merge conflict resolution process. You can trigger the merge by opening the command palette (<code>CMD</code> + <code>Shift</code> + <code>P</code>), and then type in ‚Äúgit merge‚Äù. You‚Äôll see a list of branches that you can merge into. If there is a conflict, VSCode will present this UI:</p>\n<figure>\n    \n  <a class="gatsby-resp-image-link" href="/static/gitmerge-6f12afffb9e257f466ad3578a49ae8c8-c1272.png" style="display: block" target="_blank" rel="noopener">\n  \n  <span class="gatsby-resp-image-wrapper" style="position: relative; display: block; ; max-width: 800px; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;">\n    <span class="gatsby-resp-image-background-image" style="padding-bottom: 59.1324200913242%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url(&apos;data:image/png;base64,&apos;); background-size: cover; display: block;">\n      <img class="gatsby-resp-image-image" style="width: 100%; height: 100%; margin: 0; vertical-align: middle; position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; box-shadow: inset 0px 0px 0px 400px white;" alt="Screenshot of VSCode merge conflict resolution utility" title="" src="/static/gitmerge-6f12afffb9e257f466ad3578a49ae8c8-42603.png" srcset="/static/gitmerge-6f12afffb9e257f466ad3578a49ae8c8-f931c.png 200w,\n/static/gitmerge-6f12afffb9e257f466ad3578a49ae8c8-e8031.png 400w,\n/static/gitmerge-6f12afffb9e257f466ad3578a49ae8c8-42603.png 800w,\n/static/gitmerge-6f12afffb9e257f466ad3578a49ae8c8-5b8b9.png 1200w,\n/static/gitmerge-6f12afffb9e257f466ad3578a49ae8c8-c1272.png 1314w" sizes="(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px">\n    </span>\n  </span>\n  \n  </a>\n    \n    <figcaption>VSCode makes merge conflicts easy to overcome.</figcaption>\n</figure>\n<p>Check out the ‚ÄúAccept Current Change‚Äù, ‚ÄúAccept Incoming Change‚Äù, ‚ÄúAccept Both Changes‚Äù, and ‚ÄúCompare Changes‚Äù links above the blocks. Clicking one of those will do what you expect it to. Note that you still have the save the file after accepting changes.</p>\n<h2>Tip: Common Keyboard shortcuts</h2>\n<p>Avoiding using your mouse or trackpad is vital to coding quickly. To that end, here are some keyboard shortcuts that I use often.</p>\n<p>Note that I have the <a href="https://github.com/Microsoft/vscode-sublime-keybindings">Sublime Text Keymap</a> extension installed.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><code>CMD</code> + <code>P</code> Brings up a prompt where you can type in the name of a file, hit enter, and have the file opened.</li>\n<li><code>CMD</code> + <code>Shift</code> + <code>P</code> Brings up Command Palette. I frequently use ‚ÄúChange Language Mode‚Äù.</li>\n<li><code>Opt</code> + <code>‚Üë or ‚Üì</code> Move selected text block. </li>\n<li><code>CTRL</code> + <code>CMD</code> + <code>G</code> Select all occurrences of highlighted string</li>\n<li><code>CMD</code> + <code>D</code> Select next occurrence of highlighted string</li>\n<li><code>CTRL</code> + <code>~</code> Open up the integrated console. I don‚Äôt use this daily, but it can be useful if I do not have my multiple monitors.</li>\n<li><code>Opt</code> + click a function name to go to function definition. This is called <em>Hyperclick</em>.</li>\n<li><code>CMD</code> + <code>Shift</code> + <strong>Drag Mouse</strong> - Drags a box to select text. Will not select text outside of box.</li>\n<li><code>code .</code> - From a command line, you can open up VSCode to the current directory (<a href="https://code.visualstudio.com/docs/setup/mac">setup</a>).</li>\n</ul>\n<p>VS Code allows you to easily edit your personal keyboard shortcuts pretty easily under the <strong>Preferences</strong> menu.</p>\n<p>\n  <a\n    class="gatsby-resp-image-link"\n    href="/static/keyboard-shortcuts-de3862c7e79fbe60df65c7f935030ca5-9ec73.png"\n    style="display: block"\n    target="_blank"\n    rel="noopener"\n  >\n  \n  <span\n    class="gatsby-resp-image-wrapper"\n    style="position: relative; display: block; ; max-width: 800px; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;"\n  >\n    <span\n      class="gatsby-resp-image-background-image"\n      style="padding-bottom: 60.60935799782372%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url(\'data:image/png;base64,\'); background-size: cover; display: block;"\n    >\n      <img\n        class="gatsby-resp-image-image"\n        style="width: 100%; height: 100%; margin: 0; vertical-align: middle; position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; box-shadow: inset 0px 0px 0px 400px white;"\n        alt="VSCode\'s Keyboard Shortcut Editor"\n        title=""\n        src="/static/keyboard-shortcuts-de3862c7e79fbe60df65c7f935030ca5-42603.png"\n        srcset="/static/keyboard-shortcuts-de3862c7e79fbe60df65c7f935030ca5-f931c.png 200w,\n/static/keyboard-shortcuts-de3862c7e79fbe60df65c7f935030ca5-e8031.png 400w,\n/static/keyboard-shortcuts-de3862c7e79fbe60df65c7f935030ca5-42603.png 800w,\n/static/keyboard-shortcuts-de3862c7e79fbe60df65c7f935030ca5-5b8b9.png 1200w,\n/static/keyboard-shortcuts-de3862c7e79fbe60df65c7f935030ca5-c7ea5.png 1600w,\n/static/keyboard-shortcuts-de3862c7e79fbe60df65c7f935030ca5-9ec73.png 1838w"\n        sizes="(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px"\n      />\n    </span>\n  </span>\n  \n  </a>\n    </p>\n<h2>Feature: Visual Studio Code does debugging!</h2>\n<p>Like an IDE, VSCode can debug your JavaScript (both in-browser, and Node). To get this working for Chrome, add the <a href="https://marketplace.visualstudio.com/items?itemName=msjsdiag.debugger-for-chrome">Debugger for Chrome</a> extension. You‚Äôll need to hit the gear icon to the top of the debugger‚Äôs left panel to edit the <code>launch.json</code> file to something similar to this:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>The extension operates in two modes - it can launch an instance of Chrome navigated to your app, or it can attach to a running instance of Chrome</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>The following <code>launch.json</code> config will launch a new version of Chrome. If you want to use you want to use the attach method, you need to append <code>--remote-debugging-port=9222</code> when launching Chrome. The full documentation for Chrome debugger is <a href="https://github.com/Microsoft/vscode-chrome-debug">available on GitHub</a>.</p>\n<div class="gatsby-highlight">\n      <pre class="language-json"><code>  <span class="token property">"version"</span><span class="token operator">:</span> <span class="token string">"0.2.0"</span><span class="token punctuation">,</span>\n  <span class="token property">"configurations"</span><span class="token operator">:</span> <span class="token punctuation">[</span>\n    <span class="token punctuation">{</span>\n      <span class="token property">"type"</span><span class="token operator">:</span> <span class="token string">"chrome"</span><span class="token punctuation">,</span>\n      <span class="token property">"request"</span><span class="token operator">:</span> <span class="token string">"launch"</span><span class="token punctuation">,</span>\n      <span class="token property">"name"</span><span class="token operator">:</span> <span class="token string">"Launch Chrome"</span><span class="token punctuation">,</span>\n      <span class="token property">"url"</span><span class="token operator">:</span> <span class="token string">"http://localhost:8000"</span><span class="token punctuation">,</span>\n      <span class="token property">"webRoot"</span><span class="token operator">:</span> <span class="token string">"${workspaceFolder}"</span>\n    <span class="token punctuation">}</span>\n  <span class="token punctuation">]</span>\n<span class="token punctuation">}</span>\n</code></pre>\n      </div>\n<p>To launch Chrome with the debugger enabled, click the play button ‚ñ∂Ô∏è to the top of the debugger‚Äôs left panel. Now you can set breakpoints, watch expressions, view the call stack and more. </p>\n<p>Note that VSCode can also debug Python, C++, C#, and can be integrated with PHP‚Äôs Xdebug.</p>\n<h2>Conclusion</h2>\n<p>I <em>really</em> like VSCode. To me, it boils down to the following:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>It keeps the same great features as Sublime (multiple cursors, etc)</li>\n<li>Better syntax highlighting</li>\n<li>Git integration ‚Äî specifically merge conflict resolution</li>\n<li><a href="https://code.visualstudio.com/docs">Excellent documentation</a></li>\n</ul>\n<p>That being said, I‚Äôm still very new to it. It‚Äôs going to take me months to become fully fluent in its features. But, I‚Äôm excited to get started!</p>',
excerpt:"On every new project I try to change one or two tools and/or techniques.  This is a good balance, because if I change too many things, I get‚Ä¶",frontmatter:{title:"From Sublime Text to Visual Studio Code",date:"January 28, 2018",author:null}}},pathContext:{slug:"/2018-01-28-from-sublime-to-vscode/"}}}});
